{"id":"1710.06377","submitter":"Michael Schmid","authors":"Peter Lackner, Joong Il Jake Choi, Ulrike Diebold, Michael Schmid","title":"Construction and evaluation of an ultrahigh-vacuum-compatible sputter\n  deposition source","comments":"Review of Scientific Instruments, accepted (2017)","journal-ref":"Review of Scientific Instruments 88, 103904 (2017)","doi":"10.1063/1.4998700","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mtrl-sci","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A sputter deposition source for use in ultrahigh vacuum (UHV) is described\nand some properties of the source are analyzed. The operating principle is\nbased on the design developed by Mayr et al. [Rev. Sci. Instrum. 84, 094103\n(2013)], where electrons emitted from a filament ionize argon gas, and the\nAr$^+$ ions are accelerated to the target. In contrast to the original design,\ntwo grids are used to direct a large fraction of the Ar$^+$ ions to the target,\nand the source has a housing cooled by liquid nitrogen to reduce\ncontaminations. The source has been used for deposition of zirconium, a\nmaterial that is difficult to evaporate in standard UHV evaporators. At an Ar\npressure of $9\\times 10^{-6}$ mbar in the UHV chamber and moderate emission\ncurrent, a highly reproducible deposition rate of $\\approx 1$ monolayer in 250\ns was achieved at the substrate (at a distance of $\\approx 50$ mm from the\ntarget). Higher deposition rates are easily possible. X-ray photoelectron\nspectroscopy shows a high purity of the deposited films. Depending on the grid\nvoltages, the substrate gets mildly sputtered by Ar$^+$ ions; in addition, the\nsubstrate is also reached by electrons from the negatively biased sputter\ntarget.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 17 Oct 2017 16:43:08 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-03-15"}
